\section{A Non-Self-Referential Paradox \\ in Epistemic Game Theory
}

In this section, we present a non-self-referential paradox in epistemic game theory. Unlike the BK paradox which uses   one single statement on belief and assumption of agents, this paradox consists of two sequences of players (or agents) and a sequence of statements of agent's belief and assumptions.   Indeed, this  paradox  shows that not every configuration of agents' beliefs and assumptions can be represented.   Let us consider two infinite sequence of players $\{A_i\}$ and $\{B_i\}$, with the   following description of beliefs:\\
